To make the trait `dyn` compatible with async methods, we use the `async_trait` crate which transforms async methods into ones returning boxed futures. Here's the solution:

**Cargo.toml:**
```toml
[package]
name = "async_trait_example"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
async-trait = "0.1.72"
anyhow = "1.0.80"
tokio = { version = "1.32.0", features = ["full"] }
```

**main.rs:**
```rust
use async_trait::async_trait;
use std::path::Path;
use std::sync::Arc;

#[async_trait]
pub trait RemoteActions: Send + Sync {
    async fn change_path(&mut self, from: &Path, to: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()>;
    async fn remove_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()>;
    async fn add_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()>;
    fn get_element(&self, num: usize) -> anyhow::Result<String>;
}

struct ProductionRemote;

#[async_trait]
impl RemoteActions for ProductionRemote {
    async fn change_path(&mut self, from: &Path, to: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
        println!("PROD: Moving {:?} to {:?}", from, to);
        // Actual implementation would go here
        Ok(())
    }

    async fn remove_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
        println!("PROD: Removing repo at {:?}", path);
        // Actual implementation would go here
        Ok(())
    }

    async fn add_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
        println!("PROD: Adding repo at {:?}", path);
        // Actual implementation would go here
        Ok(())
    }

    fn get_element(&self, num: usize) -> anyhow::Result<String> {
        Ok(format!("PROD: Element {}", num))
    }
}

struct TestRemote;

#[async_trait]
impl RemoteActions for TestRemote {
    async fn change_path(&mut self, _from: &Path, _to: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
        println!("TEST: Simulating path change");
        Ok(())
    }

    async fn remove_repo(&mut self, _path: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
        println!("TEST: Simulating repo removal");
        Ok(())
    }

    async fn add_repo(&mut self, _path: &Path) -> anyhow::Result<()> {
        println!("TEST: Simulating repo addition");
        Ok(())
    }

    fn get_element(&self, num: usize) -> anyhow::Result<String> {
        Ok(format!("TEST: Element {}", num))
    }
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> anyhow::Result<()> {
    let use_test = std::env::args().any(|arg| arg == "--test");

    let mut remote: Box<dyn RemoteActions> = if use_test {
        Box::new(TestRemote)
    } else {
        Box::new(ProductionRemote)
    };

    // Demonstrate async methods
    remote.add_repo(Path::new("/repo/path")).await?;
    remote.remove_repo(Path::new("/old/repo")).await?;
    remote.change_path(Path::new("/old"), Path::new("/new")).await?;

    // Demonstrate sync method
    println!("{}", remote.get_element(42)?);

    Ok(())
}
```

**Key changes made:**
1. Added `#[async_trait]` macro above the trait and implementations
2. Added `Send + Sync` bounds to the trait for thread safety
3. Implemented both `ProductionRemote` and `TestRemote` strategies
4. Used `Box<dyn RemoteActions>` for dynamic dispatch
5. Added a runtime (Tokio) with `#[tokio::main]`
6. Included example usage in `main()` showing both async and sync calls

**To test:**
1. Regular execution:
```sh
cargo run
```

2. Test mode execution:
```sh
cargo run -- --test
```

The output will show either production or test messages depending on the flag. The async methods are now fully compatible with trait objects through the `async_trait` transformation.

