To achieve high-performance animations in Kitty using the shared memory approach, I'll create a solution that leverages POSIX shared memory to avoid the overhead of base64 encoding. Here's the implementation:

Cargo.toml:
```toml
[package]
name = "kitty_animation"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
nix = "0.26.4"
rand = "0.8.5"
termion = "1.5.6"
libc = "0.2.150"
```

main.rs:
```rust
use nix::sys::mman::{shm_open, shm_unlink};
use nix::sys::mman::OFlags;
use nix::sys::mman::Mode;
use nix::unistd::ftruncate;
use rand::distributions::Alphanumeric;
use rand::{thread_rng, Rng};
use std::fs::File;
use std::io::{self, Write};
use std::os::unix::io::FromRawFd;
use std::time::{Duration, Instant};
use termion::terminal_size_pixels;

struct ShmGuard {
    name: String,
}

impl ShmGuard {
    fn new(name: &str) -> Self {
        ShmGuard {
            name: name.to_string(),
        }
    }
}

impl Drop for ShmGuard {
    fn drop(&mut self) {
        if let Err(e) = shm_unlink(&self.name) {
            eprintln!("Failed to unlink shared memory {}: {}", self.name, e);
        }
    }
}

fn generate_shm_name() -> String {
    let suffix: String = thread_rng()
        .sample_iter(Alphanumeric)
        .take(16)
        .map(char::from)
        .collect();
    format!("kitty_{}", suffix)
}

fn main() -> io::Result<()> {
    let stdout = io::stdout();
    let mut handle = stdout.lock();

    let mut time: f32 = 0.0;
    let target_fps = 60;
    let frame_duration = Duration::from_secs_f32(1.0 / target_fps as f32);
    let mut next_frame_time = Instant::now();

    loop {
        let frame_start = Instant::now();

        let (width, height) = terminal_size_pixels().unwrap_or((640, 480));
        let (width, height) = (width as usize, height as usize);

        // Generate animated RGB gradient pixel data
        let pixels: Vec<u8> = (0..height)
            .flat_map(|y| {
                (0..width).flat_map(move |x| {
                    let fx = x as f32 / width as f32;
                    let fy = y as f32 / height as f32;

                    let r = ((fx * std::f32::consts::PI + time).sin() * 0.5 + 0.5) * 255.0;
                    let g = ((fy * std::f32::consts::PI + time * 1.3).sin() * 0.5 + 0.5) * 255.0;
                    let b = (((fx + fy) * std::f32::consts::PI + time * 0.7).sin() * 0.5 + 0.5) * 255.0;

                    [r as u8, g as u8, b as u8]
                })
            })
            .collect();

        write!(handle, "\x1b[H")?;  // Move cursor to home position

        let shm_name = generate_shm_name();
        {
            // Create shared memory object
            let fd = shm_open(
                shm_name.as_str(),
                OFlags::O_CREAT | OFlags::O_RDWR | OFlags::O_EXCL,
                Mode::S_IRUSR | Mode::S_IWUSR,
            ).map_err(|e| io::Error::new(io::ErrorKind::Other, e))?;

            let _guard = ShmGuard::new(&shm_name);

            // Set size of shared memory
            ftruncate(fd, pixels.len() as i64)
                .map_err(|e| io::Error::new(io::ErrorKind::Other, e))?;

            // Write pixel data to shared memory
            let mut shm_file = unsafe { File::from_raw_fd(fd) };
            shm_file.write_all(&pixels)?;
            shm_file.flush()?;

            // Send Kitty Graphics Protocol command with shared memory reference
            write!(
                handle,
                "\x1b_Ga=T,f=24,s={},v={},shm={};\x1b\\",
                width, height, shm_name
            )?;

            handle.flush()?;
        } // Shared memory unlinked here when guard drops

        time += 0.1;

        // Maintain consistent frame rate
        let elapsed = frame_start.elapsed();
        if elapsed < frame_duration {
            std::thread::sleep(frame_duration - elapsed);
        }
        next_frame_time += frame_duration;
    }
}
```

This implementation:

1. Uses POSIX shared memory (`shm_open/shm_unlink`) to transfer pixel data
2. Generates unique shared memory names for each frame
3. Implements RAII guard to ensure proper cleanup of shared memory
4. Maintains consistent 60 FPS frame rate
5. Dynamically adapts to terminal size changes
6. Uses efficient RGB gradient animation
7. Flushes output properly to ensure frame timing

The key improvements over the base64 approach:
- Eliminates base64 encoding/decoding overhead
- Removes chunking requirements
- Reduces data transfer size by 33%
- Allows direct transfer of raw pixel data
- Maximizes animation performance

