To make the trait with async methods dyn compatible, we use the `async_trait` crate which transforms async methods into ones returning boxed futures. Here's the solution:

**Cargo.toml:**
```toml
[package]
name = "async_trait_example"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
anyhow = "1.0"
async-trait = "0.1"
tokio = { version = "1", features = ["full"] }
```

**main.rs:**
```rust
use anyhow::Result;
use async_trait::async_trait;
use std::path::Path;

#[async_trait]
pub trait RemoteActions: Send + Sync {
    async fn change_path(&mut self, from: &Path, to: &Path) -> Result<()>;
    async fn remove_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> Result<()>;
    async fn add_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> Result<()>;
    fn get_element(&self, num: usize) -> Result<String>;
}

struct ProductionStrategy;

#[async_trait]
impl RemoteActions for ProductionStrategy {
    async fn change_path(&mut self, from: &Path, to: &Path) -> Result<()> {
        println!("PRODUCTION: Moving {:?} to {:?}", from, to);
        Ok(())
    }

    async fn remove_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> Result<()> {
        println!("PRODUCTION: Removing repo at {:?}", path);
        Ok(())
    }

    async fn add_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> Result<()> {
        println!("PRODUCTION: Adding repo at {:?}", path);
        Ok(())
    }

    fn get_element(&self, num: usize) -> Result<String> {
        Ok(format!("Production element {}", num))
    }
}

struct TestStrategy;

#[async_trait]
impl RemoteActions for TestStrategy {
    async fn change_path(&mut self, from: &Path, to: &Path) -> Result<()> {
        println!("TEST: Would move {:?} to {:?}", from, to);
        Ok(())
    }

    async fn remove_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> Result<()> {
        println!("TEST: Would remove repo at {:?}", path);
        Ok(())
    }

    async fn add_repo(&mut self, path: &Path) -> Result<()> {
        println!("TEST: Would add repo at {:?}", path);
        Ok(())
    }

    fn get_element(&self, num: usize) -> Result<String> {
        Ok(format!("Test element {}", num))
    }
}

#[tokio::main]
async fn main() -> Result<()> {
    let mut strategies: Vec<Box<dyn RemoteActions>> = vec![
        Box::new(ProductionStrategy),
        Box::new(TestStrategy),
    ];

    let test_path = Path::new("/repo/path");

    for strategy in strategies.iter_mut() {
        strategy.add_repo(test_path).await?;
        strategy.change_path(test_path, Path::new("/new/path")).await?;
        strategy.remove_repo(test_path).await?;

        let element = strategy.get_element(42)?;
        println!("Got element: {}", element);
    }

    Ok(())
}
```

This solution:
1. Uses `#[async_trait]` macro to make async methods dyn-safe
2. Implements both production and test strategies
3. Shows usage of trait objects in a vector
4. Includes `Send + Sync` bounds for multithreading safety
5. Uses Tokio as the async runtime

The output will demonstrate both strategies executing:
```
