To solve the problem of storing a reference to a `Cow` within a struct while avoiding unnecessary allocations, we use a self-referential struct approach. This is achieved with the `ouroboros` crate, which allows fields to borrow from other fields within the same struct. The solution involves:

1. Defining a `ResourceRef` struct using `ouroboros` to enable self-referential borrowing.
2. Storing `dynamic_type` by value, with `group` and `kind` fields borrowing from it.
3. Implementing builder methods to construct the struct safely.
4. Providing accessor methods to retrieve borrowed data.

Here's the implementation:

### Cargo.toml
```toml
[package]
name = "cow_reference_struct"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
ouroboros = "0.15"
```

### main.rs
```rust
use ouroboros::self_referencing;
use std::borrow::Cow;

pub struct ResourceMeta {
    pub name: Option<String>,
}

pub trait Resource {
    type DynamicType: Default + Clone;

    fn meta(&self) -> &ResourceMeta;
    fn group(dyn_type: &Self::DynamicType) -> Cow<str>;
    fn kind(dyn_type: &Self::DynamicType) -> Cow<str>;
}

#[self_referencing]
#[derive(Debug, Clone)]
pub struct ResourceRef<R: Resource>
where
    R::DynamicType: Default + Clone,
{
    dynamic_type: R::DynamicType,
    #[borrows(dynamic_type)]
    group: Option<Cow<'this, str>>,
    #[borrows(dynamic_type)]
    kind: Cow<'this, str>,
    name: String,
}

impl<R: Resource> ResourceRef<R>
where
    R::DynamicType: Default + Clone,
{
    pub fn new(resource: R) -> Self {
        let name = resource
            .meta()
            .name
            .as_deref()
            .expect("Resource must have a name");
        Self::new_named(name)
    }

    pub fn new_named(name: &str) -> Self {
        ResourceRefBuilder {
            dynamic_type: R::DynamicType::default(),
            group_builder: |dyn_type: &R::DynamicType| {
                let group = R::group(dyn_type);
                if group.is_empty() {
                    None
                } else {
                    Some(group)
                }
            },
            kind_builder: |dyn_type: &R::DynamicType| R::kind(dyn_type),
            name: name.to_string(),
        }
        .build()
    }

    pub fn group(&self) -> &str {
        match self.borrow_group() {
            Some(cow) => cow.as_ref(),
            None => "",
        }
    }

    pub fn kind(&self) -> &str {
        self.borrow_kind().as_ref()
    }

    pub fn name(&self) -> &str {
        self.borrow_name()
    }
}

#[derive(Default, Clone)]
pub struct PodType;

pub struct Pod {
    meta: ResourceMeta,
}

impl Pod {
    pub fn new(name: &str) -> Self {
        Pod {
            meta: ResourceMeta {
                name: Some(name.to_string()),
            },
        }
    }
}

impl Resource for Pod {
    type DynamicType = PodType;

    fn meta(&self) -> &ResourceMeta {
        &self.meta
    }

    fn group(_: &PodType) -> Cow<str> {
        Cow::Borrowed("core")
    }

    fn kind(_: &PodType) -> Cow<str> {
        Cow::Borrowed("Pod")
    }
}

fn main() {
    let pod = Pod::new("my-pod");
    let resource_ref = ResourceRef::<Pod>::new(pod);
    println!("group: {}", resource_ref.group());
    println!("kind: {}", resource_ref.kind());
    println!("name: {}", resource_ref.name());
}
```

This code:
- Defines a `ResourceRef` struct that safely holds references to `Cow` data borrowed from its own `dynamic_type` field.
- Uses `ouroboros` to manage self-referential fields.
- Includes a sample `Pod` resource for demonstration.
- The `main` function tests the implementation by creating a `ResourceRef` and printing its fields.

