To solve the problem of downcasting `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` for any `T` without duplicating code for each type, we use a trait-based approach with dynamic dispatch. The key insight is to define a trait `Property` that can render its UI for any type, including containers like `Option` and `Vec`. This allows us to handle nested properties recursively.

### Solution
1. **Trait Definition**: The `Property` trait defines a `render_ui` method to render the property in the UI.
2. **Implementations**:
   - **Base Types**: Implement `Property` for primitive types (`i32`, `f32`, `usize`, `bool`, `String`).
   - **Containers**: Implement `Property` for `Option<T>` and `Vec<T>` where `T` implements `Property + Default`. This allows recursive handling of nested properties.
3. **Dynamic Dispatch**: Use `Box<dyn Property>` to store any type implementing `Property`, enabling dynamic downcasting via the `as_any_mut` method.
4. **UI Rendering**: The `render_property` function uses dynamic dispatch to call the appropriate `render_ui` method based on the actual type.

### Files
Here are the complete `Cargo.toml` and `main.rs` files:

#### Cargo.toml
```toml
[package]
name = "property_editor"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
egui = "0.24.0"
```

#### main.rs
```rust
use egui::{Color32, RichText, Ui};
use std::any::{Any, TypeId};
use std::fmt::Debug;

const PROPERTY_LABEL_PADDING: f32 = 10.0;

pub trait Property: Debug + 'static {
    fn render_ui(&mut self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool);
    fn as_any_mut(&mut self) -> &mut dyn Any;
}

impl<T: Debug + Any + Default + Clone> Property for Vec<T> {
    fn render_ui(&mut self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        egui::CollapsingHeader::new(title)
            .default_open(true)
            .enabled(interactable)
            .show(ui, |ui| {
                ui.horizontal_top(|ui| {
                    if ui.button("➕ Add").clicked() {
                        self.push(T::default());
                    }
                });

                let mut i = 0;
                while i < self.len() {
                    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
                        let mut item = &mut self[i];
                        render_property(ui, "", item, interactable);
                        if ui.button("❌").on_hover_text("Remove").clicked() {
                            self.remove(i);
                        } else {
                            i += 1;
                        }
                    });
                }
            });
    }

    fn as_any_mut(&mut self) -> &mut dyn Any {
        self
    }
}

impl<T: Property + Debug + Default> Property for Option<T> {
    fn render_ui(&mut self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        let mut is_none = self.is_none();
        ui.horizontal(|ui| {
            ui.label(title);
            ui.add_space(PROPERTY_LABEL_PADDING);
            bool_property(ui, "None", &mut is_none, interactable);
            ui.add_space(2.0);
            if is_none {
                *self = None;
            } else {
                if let Some(inner) = self.as_mut() {
                    render_property(ui, "", inner, interactable);
                } else {
                    *self = Some(T::default());
                }
            }
        });
    }

    fn as_any_mut(&mut self) -> &mut dyn Any {
        self
    }
}

macro_rules! impl_property_for_primitive {
    ($type:ty, $render_func:ident) => {
        impl Property for $type {
            fn render_ui(&mut self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
                $render_func(ui, title, self, interactable);
            }
            fn as_any_mut(&mut self) -> &mut dyn Any {
                self
            }
        }
    };
}

impl_property_for_primitive!(i32, i_property);
impl_property_for_primitive!(f32, f_property);
impl_property_for_primitive!(usize, i_property);
impl_property_for_primitive!(bool, bool_property);
impl_property_for_primitive!(String, string_property);

pub fn render_property(
    ui: &mut Ui,
    title: &str,
    value_mut: &mut dyn Property,
    interactable: bool,
) {
    let any = value_mut.as_any_mut();
    if let Some(string_v) = any.downcast_mut::<String>() {
        string_property(ui, title, string_v, interactable);
    } else if let Some(int_v) = any.downcast_mut::<i32>() {
        i_property(ui, title, int_v, interactable);
    } else if let Some(float_v) = any.downcast_mut::<f32>() {
        f_property(ui, title, float_v, interactable);
    } else if let Some(usize_v) = any.downcast_mut::<usize>() {
        i_property(ui, title, usize_v, interactable);
    } else if let Some(bool_v) = any.downcast_mut::<bool>() {
        bool_property(ui, title, bool_v, interactable);
    } else if let Some(opt) = any.downcast_mut::<Option<impl Property>>() {
        opt.render_ui(ui, title, interactable);
    } else if let Some(vec) = any.downcast_mut::<Vec<impl Property>>() {
        vec.render_ui(ui, title, interactable);
    } else {
        ui.label(
            RichText::new(format!("Field {}: unknown type", title))
                .color(Color32::LIGHT_RED),
        );
    }
}

// Example property rendering functions
fn string_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut String, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_space(PROPERTY_LABEL_PADDING);
        ui.text_edit_singleline(value);
    });
}

fn i_property<T: egui::emath::Numeric>(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut T, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_space(PROPERTY_LABEL_PADDING);
        ui.add(egui::DragValue::new(value));
    });
}

fn f_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut f32, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_space(PROPERTY_LABEL_PADDING);
        ui.add(egui::DragValue::new(value));
    });
}

fn bool_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut bool, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_space(PROPERTY_LABEL_PADDING);
        ui.checkbox(value, "");
    });
}

// Example usage
#[derive(Debug, Default)]
struct Data {
    vec_i32: Vec<i32>,
    vec_string: Vec<String>,
    opt_f32: Option<f32>,
    opt_bool: Option<bool>,
}

impl Property for Data {
    fn render_ui(&mut self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        egui::CollapsingHeader::new(title).show(ui, |ui| {
            render_property(ui, "Vec<i32>", &mut self.vec_i32, interactable);
            render_property(ui, "Vec<String>", &mut self.vec_string, interactable);
            render_property(ui, "Option<f32>", &mut self.opt_f32, interactable);
            render_property(ui, "Option<bool>", &mut self.opt_bool, interactable);
        });
    }

    fn as_any_mut(&mut self) -> &mut dyn Any {
        self
    }
}

fn main() {
    let options = eframe::NativeOptions::default();
    eframe::run_native(
        "Property Editor",
        options,
        Box::new(|_cc| Box::<MyApp>::default()),
    );
}

struct MyApp {
    data: Data,
}

impl Default for MyApp {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self {
            data: Data {
                vec_i32: vec![1, 2, 3],
                vec_string: vec!["a".to_string(), "b".to_string()],
                opt_f32: Some(3.14),
                opt_bool: None,
            },
        }
    }
}

impl eframe::App for MyApp {
    fn update(&mut self, ctx: &egui::Context, _frame: &mut eframe::Frame) {
        egui::CentralPanel::default().show(ctx, |ui| {
            self.data.render_ui(ui, "Data", true);
        });
    }
}
```

### Explanation
- **Trait `Property`**: Enables dynamic UI rendering for any type. The `as_any_mut` method allows downcasting to the concrete type.
- **Container Implementations**: 
  - `Vec<T>`: Renders a collapsible list with add/remove buttons.
  - `Option<T>`: Renders a checkbox to toggle between `Some` and `None`, showing the inner value when active.
- **Primitive Types**: Implement `Property` using a macro for code reuse.
- **Dynamic Dispatch**: The `render_property` function downcasts the trait object to its concrete type and calls the appropriate rendering function.
- **Example Usage**: The `Data` struct demonstrates nested properties (vectors and options) rendered recursively.

This approach eliminates code duplication for container types and handles nested properties efficiently.

