response:
To solve the problem of downcasting `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` without duplicating code for every possible `T`, we introduce a trait `PropertyWidget` that abstracts the rendering of different types. This trait is implemented for basic types, `Vec<T>` where `T: PropertyWidget`, and `Option<T>` where `T: PropertyWidget`. The `downcast_property` function then uses this trait to handle any type that implements `PropertyWidget`, reducing redundancy and simplifying the code.

### Solution Code

**Cargo.toml:**
```toml
[package]
name = "property_window"
version = "0.1.0"
edition = "2021"

[dependencies]
egui = "0.24.0"
```

**main.rs:**
```rust
use egui::{Color32, RichText, Ui};
use std::any::Any;

pub trait PropertyWidget {
    fn show(&mut self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool);
}

macro_rules! impl_property_widget_for {
    ($type:ty, $show_fn:ident) => {
        impl PropertyWidget for $type {
            fn show(&mut self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
                $show_fn(ui, title, self, interactable);
            }
        }
    };
}

impl_property_widget_for!(String, string_property);
impl_property_widget_for!(i32, i_property);
impl_property_widget_for!(f32, f_property);
impl_property_widget_for!(usize, i_property);
impl_property_widget_for!(bool, bool_property);

impl<T: PropertyWidget + Default + 'static> PropertyWidget for Vec<T> {
    fn show(&mut self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        list_property(ui, title, self, interactable);
    }
}

impl<T: PropertyWidget + Default + 'static> PropertyWidget for Option<T> {
    fn show(&mut self, ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, interactable: bool) {
        option_property(ui, title, self, interactable);
    }
}

pub fn downcast_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value_mut: &mut dyn Any, interactable: bool) {
    macro_rules! try_downcast {
        ($type:ty) => {
            if let Some(value) = value_mut.downcast_mut::<$type>() {
                value.show(ui, title, interactable);
                return;
            }
        };
    }

    try_downcast!(String);
    try_downcast!(i32);
    try_downcast!(f32);
    try_downcast!(usize);
    try_downcast!(bool);
    try_downcast!(Vec<String>);
    try_downcast!(Vec<i32>);
    try_downcast!(Vec<f32>);
    try_downcast!(Vec<usize>);
    try_downcast!(Vec<bool>);
    try_downcast!(Option<String>);
    try_downcast!(Option<i32>);
    try_downcast!(Option<f32>);
    try_downcast!(Option<usize>);
    try_downcast!(Option<bool>);

    // If no match is found, show an error
    ui.label(RichText::new(format!("Field {}: unknown type", title)).color(Color32::LIGHT_RED));
}

// Basic type property functions
fn string_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut String, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_enabled(interactable, egui::TextEdit::singleline(value));
    });
}

fn i_property<T: std::fmt::Display + std::str::FromStr>(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut T, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        let mut text = value.to_string();
        if ui.add_enabled(interactable, egui::TextEdit::singleline(&mut text)).changed() {
            if let Ok(parsed) = text.parse() {
                *value = parsed;
            }
        }
    });
}

fn f_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut f32, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_enabled(interactable, egui::DragValue::new(value).speed(0.1));
    });
}

fn bool_property(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut bool, interactable: bool) {
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        ui.add_enabled(interactable, egui::Checkbox::new(value, ""));
    });
}

// List property function
fn list_property<T: PropertyWidget + Default + 'static>(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut Vec<T>, interactable: bool) {
    egui::CollapsingHeader::new(title)
        .default_open(true)
        .enabled(interactable)
        .show(ui, |ui| {
            ui.horizontal_top(|ui| {
                if ui.button("➕ Add").clicked() {
                    value.push(T::default());
                }
            });

            let mut i = 0;
            while i < value.len() {
                ui.horizontal(|ui| {
                    value[i].show(ui, "", interactable);
                    if ui.button("❌").on_hover_text("Remove").clicked() {
                        value.remove(i);
                    } else {
                        i += 1;
                    }
                });
            }
        });
}

// Option property function
fn option_property<T: PropertyWidget + Default + 'static>(ui: &mut Ui, title: &str, value: &mut Option<T>, interactable: bool) {
    let mut is_none = value.is_none();
    ui.horizontal(|ui| {
        ui.label(title);
        bool_property(ui, "None", &mut is_none, interactable);
        if is_none {
            *value = None;
        } else {
            if value.is_none() {
                *value = Some(T::default());
            }
            if let Some(inner) = value {
                inner.show(ui, "", interactable);
            }
        }
    });
}

// Example usage
struct MyApp {
    string_value: String,
    int_value: i32,
    float_value: f32,
    bool_value: bool,
    list_of_strings: Vec<String>,
    optional_int: Option<i32>,
}

impl Default for MyApp {
    fn default() -> Self {
        Self {
            string_value: "Hello".to_string(),
            int_value: 42,
            float_value: 3.14,
            bool_value: true,
            list_of_strings: vec!["Item1".to_string(), "Item2".to_string()],
            optional_int: Some(100),
        }
    }
}

impl eframe::App for MyApp {
    fn update(&mut self, ctx: &egui::Context, _frame: &mut eframe::Frame) {
        egui::CentralPanel::default().show(ctx, |ui| {
            downcast_property(ui, "String", &mut self.string_value, true);
            downcast_property(ui, "Integer", &mut self.int_value, true);
            downcast_property(ui, "Float", &mut self.float_value, true);
            downcast_property(ui, "Boolean", &mut self.bool_value, true);
            downcast_property(ui, "List of Strings", &mut self.list_of_strings, true);
            downcast_property(ui, "Optional Integer", &mut self.optional_int, true);
        });
    }
}

fn main() {
    let options = eframe::NativeOptions::default();
    eframe::run_native(
        "Property Window Example",
        options,
        Box::new(|_cc| Box::new(MyApp::default())),
    );
}
```

### Explanation

1. **Trait Definition**: The `PropertyWidget` trait defines a `show` method to render a property in the UI.
2. **Macro for Basic Types**: The `impl_property_widget_for!` macro simplifies implementing `PropertyWidget` for basic types (e.g., `String`, `i32`).
3. **Container Implementations**: `PropertyWidget` is implemented for `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` where `T` also implements `PropertyWidget`. This allows handling any `Vec` or `Option` of a supported type without additional code.
4. **Downcast Function**: The `downcast_property` function uses a macro to attempt downcasting to supported types. If successful, it calls the `show` method. Unsupported types display an error.
5. **UI Functions**: Functions like `string_property` and `list_property` handle rendering specific types, leveraging the `PropertyWidget` trait for nested types.

This approach eliminates code duplication for `Vec<T>` and `Option<T>` by leveraging trait implementations and macros, making the code more maintainable and extensible.

